you can use the tribe_is_multiday() function wrapped around your query results. For example: That should get you where you need to be.\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Barry\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:714:\"<p>Let&#8217;s assume you&#8217;re working with code along these lines:</p>\n<pre class=\"brush: php; title: ; notranslate\">\r\n$events = tribe_get_events();\r\nforeach ($events as $event):\r\n\r\n    // ... Code to print out event details ...\r\n\r\nendforeach;\r\n</pre>\n<p>You may wish to ignore multiday events, however. In that case, you can use the <em>tribe_is_multiday()</em> function wrapped around your query results. For example:</p>\n<pre class=\"brush: php; title: ; notranslate\">\r\n$events = tribe_get_events();\r\nforeach ($events as $event):\r\n    if (! tribe_event_is_multiday()):\r\n\r\n        // ... Code to print out event details ...\r\n\r\n    endif;\r\nendforeach;\r\n</pre>\n<p>That should get you where you need to be.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:69:\"http://tri.be/querying-ongoing-and-single-day-events-separately/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:56:\"Altering or Removing Headings on Calendar and List Views\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:38:\"http://tri.be/alter-or-remove-heading/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:47:\"http://tri.be/alter-or-remove-heading/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 02 Jul 2013 21:47:32 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Tutorial\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:22:\"http://tri.be/?p=49847\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:534:\"All of the default views contain a title normally located just under the events bar. In the example below we can see that the title on the list view is Upcoming Events, for example. It may be that you consider this to be superfluous and wish to remove it completely or perhaps change it slightly. If we wished to change this text to something domain-specific, such as Upcoming Parties, then we could accomplish this by &#8230; <a href=\"http://tri.be/alter-or-remove-heading/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&#8594;</span></a>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Barry\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2243:\"<p>All of the default views contain a title normally located just under the events bar. In the example below we can see that the title on the list view is <em>Upcoming Events,</em> for example. It may be that you consider this to be superfluous and wish to remove it completely or perhaps change it slightly.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://tri.be/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/tutorial-titles-default-title-list-view.png\"></a></p>\n<p>If we wished to change this text to something domain-specific, such as <em>Upcoming Parties,</em> then we could accomplish this by adding a short snippet to our theme&#8217;s functions.php file.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://tri.be/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/codegrab-filter-upcoming-titles.png\"></a></p>\n<p>Of course, it could alternatively be the case that we want to remove the <em>Upcoming Events</em> title from list views entirely. Setting up a filter as we did above isn&#8217;t going to be ideal in that situation &#8211; as doing so would leave an empty header element in place.</p>\n<p>Instead, we could use a template override in this scenario (if you haven&#8217;t already done so, please take the time to review our <a href=\"http://tri.be/support/documentation/events-calendar-themers-guide/\">Themer&#8217;s Guide</a> before moving forward &#8211; it contains answers to a ton of commonly asked questions about this process).</p>\n<p>In essence this means copying the original template &#8211; in this case, <em>list.php</em> &#8211; from it&#8217;s home at:</p>\n<pre>wp-content/plugins/the-events-calendar/views/list/content.php</pre>\n<p>And placing it in (you may need to create some extra directories here):</p>\n<pre>wp-content/themes/{YOUR_THEME}/tribe-events/list/content.php</pre>\n<p>Now open it up and simply locate and remove the following line of code:</p>\n<p><code>&lt;h2 class=\"tribe-events-page-title\"&gt;&lt;?php echo tribe_get_events_title() ?&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;</code></p>\n<p>Note that the title will now be removed from the list view but will remain in place in the map view. However the process to remove it from that view is pretty much the same &#8211; you would simply need to locate the map template within the <em>Events Calendar PRO</em> directory first of all and repeat the process with it.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:43:\"http://tri.be/alter-or-remove-heading/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"2\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:22:\"What’s in a License?\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"http://tri.be/whats-in-a-license/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"http://tri.be/whats-in-a-license/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";